[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] The method constructs a probabilistic model of the unknown function, often a Gaussian process (GP), and uses the resulting predictive distribution to choose the next evaluation point.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] This choice is made by optimizing a sampling criterion, also called an acquisition function.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Common applications include hyperparameter optimization in machine learning, where each trial may require training and validating a model, and engineering design problems driven by expensive numerical simulations.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Early Bayesian approaches to global optimization include work by Harold J.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Kushner on locating extrema of noisy functions and work by Jonas Mockus on Bayesian methods for seeking extrema.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Expected improvement is a prominent sampling criterion in this line of work.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Jones, Matthias Schonlau, and William J.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Welch introduced the efficient global optimization (EGO) algorithm, which used a kriging or Gaussian-process model with expected improvement for expensive black-box functions.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Later work extended Bayesian optimization to noisy observations, constraints, batch and parallel evaluations, multiple objectives, and mixed or high-dimensional search spaces.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] where ${\mathcal {X}}$ is a search space and f is an unknown objective function.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] A maximization problem can be written in the same form by minimizing $-f$ .
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Although the search space may in principle be continuous, discrete, categorical, or mixed, the standard formulation is most directly applicable to continuous, low- to moderate-dimensional domains.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Later methods attempt to relax these restrictions by addressing mixed variables, high-dimensional spaces, constraints, parallel evaluations, and multiple objectives.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] A useful distinction is between *noiseless* and *noisy* optimization.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Many real applications also involve constraints, parallel evaluations, or multiple objectives.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] These variants change how the probabilistic model, incumbent solution, and sampling criterion are defined.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] A typical Bayesian optimization procedure builds a sequence of evaluation points.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Starting from an initial design $X_{0}$ , the algorithm produces additional evaluation points $x_{1},x_{2},\ldots$ .
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] After n sequential evaluations, $X_{n}=X_{0}\cup \{x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}\}$ denotes the evaluated points and ${\mathcal {D}}_{n}$ denotes the corresponding observations.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] The next point $x_{n+1}$ , or a batch of points, is selected by optimizing a sampling criterion computed from the current probabilistic model.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Evaluate the objective function, and any constraints if present, at the initial design points.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Construct or update a probabilistic model using the observed data ${\mathcal {D}}_{n}$ .
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Define a sampling criterion, also called an acquisition function or infill criterion, from the probabilistic model.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Optimize the sampling criterion to select $x_{n+1}$ , or a batch of points, for evaluation.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Evaluate the selected point or points and update the data set.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Repeat until an evaluation budget, convergence criterion, or stopping rule is reached.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] The Bayesian strategy treats the unknown objective as a random function and places a prior over it.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] The prior captures assumptions about the behavior of the function.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] After observations are collected, the prior is updated to form a posterior distribution over the objective function.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] The posterior distribution is then used to construct the sampling criterion that determines the next query point.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Bayesian optimization requires a probabilistic model of the unknown objective function and, when present, of unknown constraints.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Given the evaluations observed so far, the model gives a predictive distribution for unevaluated points in the search space.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Sampling criteria are defined from this predictive distribution, so the model provides both predicted objective values and uncertainty estimates.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Such probabilistic models are often called surrogate models or metamodels because they are used in place of direct evaluations of the expensive objective when choosing candidate points.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Gaussian process regression is the standard probabilistic model in classical presentations of Bayesian optimization and remains common in applications.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] A Gaussian process prior defines a distribution over functions.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] After observations are collected, the posterior predictive mean and variance are used by sampling criteria such as expected improvement, probability of improvement, and upper confidence bound criteria.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Other probabilistic models can be used when the search space, dimensionality, or data size favors another representation.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Bayesian optimization is often described through a noiseless, single-objective problem, but the same model-based loop is adapted to several related settings.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] In noisy Bayesian optimization, evaluations return observations such as $y=f(x)+\varepsilon$ instead of exact values of the latent objective.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] The probabilistic model can represent both uncertainty about f and observation noise.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Classical expected improvement over the best observed value is a noiseless criterion.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] In noisy settings, recommendation rules and sampling criteria may be defined for the latent objective, for future noisy observations, or for the value of information.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Examples include knowledge-gradient and information-theoretic criteria.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] In constrained Bayesian optimization, the objective is optimized subject to feasibility constraints.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] If the constraints are also unknown black-box functions, separate probabilistic models can be constructed for the objective and constraints, and the sampling criterion can combine predicted improvement with the probability of feasibility.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] In batch or parallel Bayesian optimization, the method proposes several candidate points before the corresponding observations are available.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Batch methods are useful when experiments, simulations, or machine-learning jobs can be executed concurrently.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] They may optimize a joint sampling criterion or choose points sequentially while accounting for pending evaluations.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] In multi-objective Bayesian optimization, several objective functions are optimized at once and the result is typically an approximation to a Pareto front.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Methods include scalarization approaches such as ParEGO, which reduce the problem to a sequence of single-objective subproblems, and indicator-based approaches using criteria such as expected hypervolume improvement.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Constrained multi-objective Bayesian optimization combines these extensions by modeling objectives and constraints and using sampling criteria based on extended domination rules and expected hypervolume improvement.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] A sampling criterion, also called an acquisition function in the machine-learning literature or an infill criterion in surrogate-based optimization, scores candidate points using the current predictive distribution.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] It is usually inexpensive to evaluate and is optimized instead of the expensive objective function.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Sampling criteria express the exploration-exploitation tradeoff by assigning high values to points with a low predicted objective value, high uncertainty, or both.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] A seminal example in the noiseless setting is expected improvement, which scores a candidate point by the posterior expected gain over the best value observed so far.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Expected improvement (EI) was used in the efficient global optimization (EGO) algorithm and remains a standard reference criterion for noiseless Bayesian optimization.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] In the noiseless minimization setting, let $f_{\min }$ be the best objective value observed so far and let ${\mathcal {D}}$ denote the data.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] where $\Phi$ and $\phi$ are the cumulative distribution function and probability density function of the standard normal distribution.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] EI is therefore large when the model predicts a low objective value, when uncertainty is high, or both.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] The sampling criterion is usually cheap to evaluate relative to the objective, but optimizing it can still be a nonconvex auxiliary problem.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Its optimum is often sought by discretization, multi-start local optimization, or deterministic numerical methods such as Newton's method and quasi-Newton methods like the Broyden–Fletcher–Goldfarb–Shanno algorithm.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Stochastic methods are also used for this auxiliary search, especially for multimodal or mixed-variable criteria.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Examples include genetic algorithms and other evolutionary algorithms, as well as sequential Monte Carlo methods.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Several derivative-free optimization methods use probability distributions without modeling the unknown objective function itself.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Estimation of distribution algorithms build and sample explicit probabilistic models of selected candidate solutions.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] The cross-entropy method and CMA-ES also update parametric sampling distributions, with CMA-ES adapting the mean, step size, and covariance matrix of a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] These methods use objective values to update a distribution over candidate points.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] In Bayesian optimization, the probabilistic model instead represents the objective or constraints, and the next point is chosen by optimizing a criterion derived from that model.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Gaussian-process sequential design is also used in reliability analysis to estimate a probability of failure.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] For a limit-state function f , random input X , and threshold t , the target may be $\mathbb {P} (f(X)\leq t)$ , or more generally the measure of an excursion set.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Stepwise uncertainty reduction strategies choose evaluations to reduce uncertainty about this probability, rather than to locate the minimizer or maximizer of f .
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Bayesian optimization is also related to multi-armed bandit problems.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Both study sequential decisions that trade off exploration and exploitation, and criteria such as upper confidence bounds and Thompson sampling appear in both settings.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] A common distinction is that bandit algorithms are often formulated to control cumulative regret over a sequence of actions, while Bayesian optimization often emphasizes finding a good optimizer of an expensive function after a small evaluation budget.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Bayesian optimization is used in applications where objective evaluations are costly.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/bayesian-optimization] Examples discussed in surveys and textbooks include hyperparameter optimization and algorithm configuration, engineering design and simulation-based optimization, robotics, sensor networks, and experimental design in the physical sciences.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] In a prediction problem, a model is usually given a dataset of *known data* on which training is run (*training dataset*), and a dataset of *unknown data* (or *first seen* data) against which the model is tested (called the validation dataset or *testing set*).
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] One round of cross-validation involves partitioning a sample of data into complementary subsets, performing the analysis on one subset (called the *training set*), and validating the analysis on the other subset (called the *validation set* or *testing set*).
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] To reduce variability, in most methods multiple rounds of cross-validation are performed using different partitions, and the validation results are combined (e.g. averaged) over the rounds to give an estimate of the model's predictive performance.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] In summary, cross-validation combines (averages) measures of fitness in prediction to derive a more accurate estimate of model prediction performance.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Assume a model with one or more unknown parameters, and a data set to which the model can be fit (the training data set).
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] The fitting process optimizes the model parameters to make the model fit the training data as well as possible.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] If an independent sample of validation data is taken from the same population as the training data, it will generally turn out that the model does not fit the validation data as well as it fits the training data.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] The size of this difference is likely to be large especially when the size of the training data set is small, or when the number of parameters in the model is large.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Cross-validation is a way to estimate the size of this effect.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] If least squares is used to fit a function in the form of a hyperplane ***ŷ*** = *a* + ***β***T***x*** to the data (***x****i*, *y**i*) 1 ≤ *i* ≤ *n*, then the fit can be assessed using the mean squared error (MSE).
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] If the model is correctly specified, it can be shown under mild assumptions that the expected value of the MSE for the training set is (*n* − *p* − 1)/(*n* + *p* + 1) < 1 times the expected value of the MSE for the validation set (the expected value is taken over the distribution of training sets).
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Thus, a fitted model and computed MSE on the training set will result in an optimistically biased assessment of how well the model will fit an independent data set.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] This biased estimate is called the *in-sample* estimate of the fit, whereas the cross-validation estimate is an *out-of-sample* estimate.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] In most other regression procedures (e.g. logistic regression), there is no simple formula to compute the expected out-of-sample fit.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Cross-validation is, thus, a generally applicable way to predict the performance of a model on unavailable data using numerical computation in place of theoretical analysis.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Two types of cross-validation can be distinguished: exhaustive and non-exhaustive cross-validation.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Exhaustive cross-validation methods are cross-validation methods which learn and test on all possible ways to divide the original sample into a training and a validation set.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Leave-*p*-out cross-validation (**LpO CV**) involves using *p* observations as the validation set and the remaining observations as the training set.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] This is repeated on all ways to cut the original sample on a validation set of *p* observations and a training set.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] LpO cross-validation require training and validating the model $C_{p}^{n}$ times, where *n* is the number of observations in the original sample, and where $C_{p}^{n}$ is the binomial coefficient.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] For *p* > 1 and for even moderately large *n*, LpO CV can become computationally infeasible.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] A variant of LpO cross-validation with p=2 known as leave-pair-out cross-validation has been recommended as a nearly unbiased method for estimating the area under ROC curve of binary classifiers.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Leave-*one*-out cross-validation (**LOOCV**) is a particular case of leave-*p*-out cross-validation with *p* = 1.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] The process looks similar to jackknife; however, with cross-validation one computes a statistic on the left-out sample(s), while with jackknifing one computes a statistic from the kept samples only.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] LOO cross-validation requires less computation time than LpO cross-validation because there are only $C_{1}^{n}=n$ passes rather than $C_{p}^{n}$ .
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] However, n passes may still require quite a large computation time, in which case other approaches such as k-fold cross validation may be more appropriate.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Non-exhaustive cross validation methods do not compute all ways of splitting the original sample.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] These methods are approximations of leave-*p*-out cross-validation.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] In *k*-fold cross-validation, the original sample is randomly partitioned into *k* equal sized subsamples, often referred to as "folds".
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Of the *k* subsamples, a single subsample is retained as the validation data for testing the model, and the remaining *k* − 1 subsamples are used as training data.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] The cross-validation process is then repeated *k* times, with each of the *k* subsamples used exactly once as the validation data.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] The *k* results can then be averaged to produce a single estimation.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] The advantage of this method over repeated random sub-sampling (see below) is that all observations are used for both training and validation, and each observation is used for validation exactly once.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] 10-fold cross-validation is commonly used, but in general *k* remains an unfixed parameter.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] For example, setting *k* = *2* results in 2-fold cross-validation.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] In 2-fold cross-validation, the dataset is randomly shuffled into two sets *d*0 and *d*1, so that both sets are equal size (this is usually implemented by shuffling the data array and then splitting it in two).
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] We then train on *d*0 and validate on *d*1, followed by training on *d*1 and validating on *d*0.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] When *k* = *n* (the number of observations), *k*-fold cross-validation is equivalent to leave-one-out cross-validation.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] In *stratified* *k*-fold cross-validation, the partitions are selected so that the mean response value is approximately equal in all the partitions.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] In the case of binary classification, this means that each partition contains roughly the same proportions of the two types of class labels.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] In *repeated* cross-validation the data is randomly split into *k* partitions several times.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] The performance of the model can thereby be averaged over several runs, but this is rarely desirable in practice.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] When many different statistical or machine learning models are being considered, *greedy* *k*-fold cross-validation can be used to quickly identify the most promising candidate models.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] In the holdout method, we randomly assign data points to two sets *d*0 and *d*1, usually called the training set and the test set, respectively.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] The size of each of the sets is arbitrary although typically the test set is smaller than the training set.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] We then train (build a model) on *d*0 and test (evaluate its performance) on *d*1.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] In typical cross-validation, results of multiple runs of model-testing are averaged together; in contrast, the holdout method, in isolation, involves a single run.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] It should be used with caution because without such averaging of multiple runs, one may achieve highly misleading results.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] One's indicator of predictive accuracy (*F**) will tend to be unstable since it will not be smoothed out by multiple iterations (see below).
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Similarly, indicators of the specific role played by various predictor variables (e.g., values of regression coefficients) will tend to be unstable.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] While the holdout method can be framed as "the simplest kind of cross-validation", many sources instead classify holdout as a type of simple validation, rather than a simple or degenerate form of cross-validation.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] This method, also known as Monte Carlo cross-validation, creates multiple random splits of the dataset into training and validation data.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] For each such split, the model is fit to the training data, and predictive accuracy is assessed using the validation data.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] The results are then averaged over the splits.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] The advantage of this method (over *k*-fold cross validation) is that the proportion of the training/validation split is not dependent on the number of iterations (i.e., the number of partitions).
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] The disadvantage of this method is that some observations may never be selected in the validation subsample, whereas others may be selected more than once.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] In other words, validation subsets may overlap.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] This method also exhibits Monte Carlo variation, meaning that the results will vary if the analysis is repeated with different random splits.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] As the number of random splits approaches infinity, the result of repeated random sub-sampling validation tends towards that of leave-p-out cross-validation.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] In a stratified variant of this approach, the random samples are generated in such a way that the mean response value (i.e. the dependent variable in the regression) is equal in the training and testing sets.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] This is particularly useful if the responses are dichotomous with an unbalanced representation of the two response values in the data.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] A method that applies repeated random sub-sampling is RANSAC.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] When cross-validation is used simultaneously for selection of the best set of hyperparameters and for error estimation (and assessment of generalization capacity), a nested cross-validation is required.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] This is a truly nested variant which contains an outer loop of *k* sets and an inner loop of *l* sets.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] The total data set is split into *k* sets.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] One by one, a set is selected as the (outer) test set and the *k* - 1 other sets are combined into the corresponding outer training set.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] This is repeated for each of the *k* sets.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Each outer training set is further sub-divided into *l* sets.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] One by one, a set is selected as inner test (validation) set and the *l* - 1 other sets are combined into the corresponding inner training set.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] This is repeated for each of the *l* sets.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] The inner training sets are used to fit model parameters, while the inner test set is used as a validation set to provide an unbiased evaluation of the model fit.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Typically, this is repeated for many different hyperparameters (or even different model types) and the validation set is used to determine the best hyperparameter set (and model type) for this inner training set.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] After this, a new model is fit on the entire outer training set, using the best set of hyperparameters from the inner cross-validation.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] The performance of this model is then evaluated using the outer test set.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] This is a type of k*l-fold cross-validation when *l* = *k* - 1.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] A single k-fold cross-validation is used with both a validation and test set.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] One by one, a set is selected as test set.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Then, one by one, one of the remaining sets is used as a validation set and the other *k* - 2 sets are used as training sets until all possible combinations have been evaluated.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Similar to the k*l-fold cross validation, the training set is used for model fitting and the validation set is used for model evaluation for each of the hyperparameter sets.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Finally, for the selected parameter set, the test set is used to evaluate the model with the best parameter set.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Here, two variants are possible: either evaluating the model that was trained on the training set or evaluating a new model that was fit on the combination of the training and the validation set.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] The goal of cross-validation is to estimate the expected level of fit of a model to a data set that is independent of the data that were used to train the model.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] It can be used to estimate any quantitative measure of fit that is appropriate for the data and model.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] For example, for binary classification problems, each case in the validation set is either predicted correctly or incorrectly.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] In this situation the misclassification error rate can be used to summarize the fit, although other measures derived from information (e.g., counts, frequency) contained within a contingency table or confusion matrix could also be used.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] When the value being predicted is continuously distributed, the mean squared error, root mean squared error or median absolute deviation could be used to summarize the errors.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] When users apply cross-validation to select a good configuration $\lambda$ , then they might want to balance the cross-validated choice with their own estimate of the configuration.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] In this way, they can attempt to counter the volatility of cross-validation when the sample size is small and include relevant information from previous research.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] In a forecasting combination exercise, for instance, cross-validation can be applied to estimate the weights that are assigned to each forecast.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Since a simple equal-weighted forecast is difficult to beat, a penalty can be added for deviating from equal weights.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Or, if cross-validation is applied to assign individual weights to observations, then one can penalize deviations from equal weights to avoid wasting potentially relevant information.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Hoornweg (2018) shows how a tuning parameter $\gamma$ can be defined so that a user can intuitively balance between the accuracy of cross-validation and the simplicity of sticking to a reference parameter $\lambda _{R}$ that is defined by the user.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Relative accuracy can be quantified as ${\mbox{MSE}}(\lambda _{i})/{\mbox{MSE}}(\lambda _{R})$ , so that the mean squared error of a candidate $\lambda _{i}$ is made relative to that of a user-specified $\lambda _{R}$ .
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] The relative simplicity term measures the amount that $\lambda _{i}$ deviates from $\lambda _{R}$ relative to the maximum amount of deviation from $\lambda _{R}$ .
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Accordingly, relative simplicity can be specified as ${\frac {(\lambda _{i}-\lambda _{R})^{2}}{(\lambda _{\max }-\lambda _{R})^{2}}}$ , where $\lambda _{\max }$ corresponds to the $\lambda$ value with the highest permissible deviation from $\lambda _{R}$ .
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] With $\gamma \in [0,1]$ , the user determines how high the influence of the reference parameter is relative to cross-validation.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Hoornweg (2018) shows that a loss function with such an accuracy-simplicity tradeoff can also be used to intuitively define shrinkage estimators like the (adaptive) lasso and Bayesian / ridge regression.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Suppose we choose a measure of fit *F*, and use cross-validation to produce an estimate *F** of the expected fit *EF* of a model to an independent data set drawn from the same population as the training data.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] If we imagine sampling multiple independent training sets following the same distribution, the resulting values for *F** will vary.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] The statistical properties of *F** result from this variation.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] For this reason, if two statistical procedures are compared based on the results of cross-validation, the procedure with the better estimated performance may not actually be the better of the two procedures (i.e. it may not have the better value of *EF*).
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Some progress has been made on constructing confidence intervals around cross-validation estimates, but this is considered a difficult problem.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Most forms of cross-validation are straightforward to implement as long as an implementation of the prediction method being studied is available.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] In particular, the prediction method can be a "black box" – there is no need to have access to the internals of its implementation.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] If the prediction method is expensive to train, cross-validation can be very slow since the training must be carried out repeatedly.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] In some cases such as least squares and kernel regression, cross-validation can be sped up significantly by pre-computing certain values that are needed repeatedly in the training, or by using fast "updating rules" such as the Sherman–Morrison formula.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] However one must be careful to preserve the "total blinding" of the validation set from the training procedure, otherwise bias may result.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] An extreme example of accelerating cross-validation occurs in linear regression, where the results of cross-validation have a closed-form expression known as the *prediction residual error sum of squares* (PRESS).
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Cross-validation only yields meaningful results if the validation set and training set are drawn from the same population and only if human biases are controlled.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] In many applications of predictive modeling, the structure of the system being studied evolves over time (i.e. it is "non-stationary").
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Both of these can introduce systematic differences between the training and validation sets.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] For example, if a model for prediction of trend changes in financial quotations is trained on data for a certain five-year period, it is unrealistic to treat the subsequent five-year period as a draw from the same population.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] As another example, suppose a model is developed to predict an individual's risk for being diagnosed with a particular disease within the next year.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] If the model is trained using data from a study involving only a specific population group (e.g. young people or males), but is then applied to the general population, the cross-validation results from the training set could differ greatly from the actual predictive performance.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] In many applications, models also may be incorrectly specified and vary as a function of modeler biases and/or arbitrary choices.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] When this occurs, there may be an illusion that the system changes in external samples, whereas the reason is that the model has missed a critical predictor and/or included a confounded predictor.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] New evidence is that cross-validation by itself is not very predictive of external validity, whereas a form of experimental validation known as swap sampling that does control for human bias can be much more predictive of external validity.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] As defined by this large MAQC-II study across 30,000 models, swap sampling incorporates cross-validation in the sense that predictions are tested across independent training and validation samples.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Yet, models are also developed across these independent samples and by modelers who are blinded to one another.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] When there is a mismatch in these models developed across these swapped training and validation samples as happens quite frequently, MAQC-II shows that this will be much more predictive of poor external predictive validity than traditional cross-validation.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] The reason for the success of the swapped sampling is a built-in control for human biases in model building.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Due to correlations, cross-validation with random splits might be problematic for time-series models (if we are more interested in evaluating extrapolation, rather than interpolation).
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] A more appropriate approach might be to use rolling cross-validation.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] However, if performance is described by a single summary statistic, it is possible that the approach described by Politis and Romano as a stationary bootstrap will work.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] The statistic of the bootstrap needs to accept an interval of the time series and return the summary statistic on it.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] The call to the stationary bootstrap needs to specify an appropriate mean interval length.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Similar challenges occur with spatial and spatiotemporal data, where spatial autocorrelation can lead to overly optimistic error estimates when random splits are used.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Spatial blocking methods partition data into geographically distinct blocks, while buffered spatial cross-validation adds separation zones between training and test sets to reduce spatial leakage.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] A related technique is to use a clustering algorithm for creating environmentally distinct clusters, to specifically test how well a spatial model can generalize from one environmental context to another.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] For spatiotemporal models, spatial blocking can be combined with rolling or forward-chaining temporal splits to account for both spatial and temporal dependence.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] A recent review summarises cross-validation strategies for spatiotemporal statistics, outlining their theoretical foundations, computational challenges, and applications across environmental and econometric contexts.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Cross-validation can be used to compare the performances of different predictive modeling procedures.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] For example, suppose we are interested in optical character recognition, and we are considering using either a Support Vector Machine (SVM) or *k*-nearest neighbors (KNN) to predict the true character from an image of a handwritten character.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Using cross-validation, we can obtain empirical estimates comparing these two methods in terms of their respective fractions of misclassified characters.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] In contrast, the in-sample estimate will not represent the quantity of interest (i.e. the generalization error).
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Cross-validation can also be used in *variable selection*.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] Suppose we are using the expression levels of 20 proteins to predict whether a cancer patient will respond to a drug.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] A practical goal would be to determine which subset of the 20 features should be used to produce the best predictive model.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] For most modeling procedures, if we compare feature subsets using the in-sample error rates, the best performance will occur when all 20 features are used.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] However under cross-validation, the model with the best fit will generally include only a subset of the features that are deemed truly informative.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] A recent development in medical statistics is its use in meta-analysis.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] It forms the basis of the validation statistic, Vn which is used to test the statistical validity of meta-analysis summary estimates.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/cross-validation-statistics] It has also been used in a more conventional sense in meta-analysis to estimate the likely prediction error of meta-analysis results.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/gaussian-process] In probability theory and statistics, a **Gaussian process** is a stochastic process (a collection of random variables indexed by time or space), such that every finite collection of those random variables has a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/gaussian-process] The distribution of a Gaussian process is the joint distribution of all those (infinitely many) random variables, and as such, it is a distribution over functions with a continuous domain, e.g. time or space.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/gaussian-process] The concept of Gaussian processes is named after Carl Friedrich Gauss because it is based on the notion of the Gaussian distribution (normal distribution).
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/gaussian-process] Gaussian processes can be seen as an infinite-dimensional generalization of multivariate normal distributions.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/gaussian-process] Gaussian processes are useful in statistical modelling, benefiting from properties inherited from the normal distribution.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/gaussian-process] For example, if a random process is modelled as a Gaussian process, the distributions of various derived quantities can be obtained explicitly.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/gaussian-process] Such quantities include the average value of the process over a range of times and the error in estimating the average using sample values at a small set of times.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/gaussian-process] While exact models often scale poorly as the amount of data increases, multiple approximation methods have been developed which often retain good accuracy while drastically reducing computation time.
