[src:hyperparameter-tuning/gaussian-process] A key fact of Gaussian processes is that they can be completely defined by their second-order statistics.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/gaussian-process] Thus, if a Gaussian process is assumed to have mean zero, defining the covariance function completely defines the process' behaviour.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/gaussian-process] Importantly the non-negative definiteness of this function enables its spectral decomposition using the Karhunen–Loève expansion.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/gaussian-process] Basic aspects that can be defined through the covariance function are the process' stationarity, isotropy, smoothness and periodicity.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/gaussian-process] Stationarity refers to the process' behaviour regarding the separation of any two points x and $x'$ .
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/gaussian-process] If the process is stationary, the covariance function depends only on $x-x'$ .
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/gaussian-process] For example, the Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process is stationary.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/gaussian-process] If the process depends only on $|x-x'|$ , the Euclidean distance (not the direction) between x and $x'$ , then the process is considered isotropic.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/gaussian-process] A process that is concurrently stationary and isotropic is considered to be homogeneous; in practice these properties reflect the differences (or rather the lack of them) in the behaviour of the process given the location of the observer.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/gaussian-process] Ultimately Gaussian processes translate as taking priors on functions and the smoothness of these priors can be induced by the covariance function.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/gaussian-process] If we expect that for "near-by" input points x and $x'$ their corresponding output points y and $y'$ to be "near-by" also, then the assumption of continuity is present.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/gaussian-process] If we wish to allow for significant displacement then we might choose a rougher covariance function.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/gaussian-process] Extreme examples of the behaviour is the Ornstein–Uhlenbeck covariance function and the squared exponential where the former is never differentiable and the latter infinitely differentiable.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/gaussian-process] Periodicity refers to inducing periodic patterns within the behaviour of the process.
[src:hyperparameter-tuning/gaussian-process] Formally, this is achieved by mapping the input x to a two dimensional vector $u(x)=\left(\cos(x),\sin(x)\right)$ .
